# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cornish-engine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Steam power has generally been superseded by the internal combustion engine or by electrical power drawn from an electrical grid.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The only steam installations that are in widespread use are the highly efficient thermal power plants used for generating electricity on a large scale.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] In contrast, the proposed steam engines may be for stationary, road, rail, or marine use.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Although most references to "Modern Steam" apply to developments since the 1970s, certain aspects of advanced steam technology can be discerned throughout the 20th century, notably automatic boiler control along with rapid startup.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] In 1922, Abner Doble developed an electro-mechanical system that reacted simultaneously to steam temperature and pressure, starting and stopping the feed pumps whilst igniting and cutting out the burner according to boiler pressure.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The contraflow monotube boiler had a working pressure of 750–1,200 psi (5.17–8.27 MPa) but contained so little water in circulation as to present no risk of explosion.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] This type of boiler was continuously developed in the US, Britain and Germany throughout the 1930s and into the 1950s for use in cars, buses, trucks, railcars, shunting locomotives (US; switchers), a speedboat and, in 1933, a converted Travel Air 2000 biplane.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] In the UK, Sentinel Waggon Works developed a vertical water-tube boiler running at 275 psi (1.90 MPa) which was used in road vehicles, shunting locomotives and railcars.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Steam could be raised much more quickly than with a conventional locomotive boiler.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Trials of the Anderson condensing system took place on Britain's Southern Railway between 1930 and 1935.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Anderson condensing system uses a process known as mechanical vapor recompression.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] It was devised by a Glasgow marine engineer, Harry Percival Harvey Anderson.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The theory was that, by removing around 600 of the 970 British thermal units present in each pound of steam (1400 of the 2260 kilojoules in each kilogram), it would be possible to return the exhaust steam to the boiler by a pump which would consume only 1–2% of the engine's power output.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Between 1925 and 1927 Anderson, and another Glasgow engineer John McCullum (some sources give McCallum), conducted experiments on a stationary steam plant with encouraging results.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A company, Steam Heat Conservation (SHC), was formed and a demonstration of Anderson's system was arranged at Surbiton Electricity Generating Station.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] SHC was interested in applying the system to a railway locomotive and contacted Richard Maunsell of the Southern Railway.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Maunsell requested that a controlled test be carried out at Surbiton and this was done about 1929.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Maunsell's technical assistant, Harold Holcroft, was present and a fuel saving of 29% was recorded, compared to conventional atmospheric working.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Southern Railway converted SECR N class locomotive number A816 (later 1816 and 31816) to the Anderson system in 1930.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The locomotive underwent trials and initial results were encouraging.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The trials continued until 1934 but various problems arose, mostly with the fan for forced draught, and the project went no further.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The locomotive was converted back to standard form in 1935.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The work of French mechanical engineer André Chapelon in applying scientific analysis and a strive for thermal efficiency was an early example of advanced steam technology.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Chapelon's protégé Livio Dante Porta continued Chapelon's work.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Postwar in the late 1940s and 1950s some designers worked on modernising steam locomotives.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Argentinian engineer Livio Dante Porta in the development of Stephensonian railway locomotives incorporating advanced steam technology was a precursor of the 'Modern Steam' movement from 1948.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Where possible, Porta much preferred to design new locomotives, but more often in practice he was forced to radically update old ones to incorporate the new technology.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] 1949 by Oliver Bulleid and the British Rail ‘Standard’ class steam locomotives of the 1950s by Robert Riddles, particularly the BR Standard Class 9F, were used to trial new steam locomotive design features, including the Franco-Crosti boiler.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] On moving to Ireland, Bulleid also designed CIÉ No.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Sir Biscoe Tritton Lecture, given by Roger Waller, of the DLM company to the Institute of Mechanical Engineers in 2003 gives an idea of how problems in steam power are being addressed.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Waller refers mainly to some rack and pinion mountain railway locomotives that were newly built from 1992 to 1998.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] They were developed for three companies in Switzerland and Austria and continued to work on two of these lines as of 2008.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The new steam locomotives burn the same grade of light oil as their diesel counterparts, and all demonstrate the same advantages of ready availability and reduced labour cost; at the same time, they have been shown to greatly reduce air and ground pollution.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Their economic superiority has meant that they have largely replaced the diesel locomotives and railcars previously operating the line; additionally, steam locomotives are a tourist attraction.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A parallel line of development was the return to steam power of the old Lake Geneva paddle steamer *Montreux* that had been refitted with a diesel-electric engine in the 1960s.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Economic aims similar to those achieved with the rack locomotives were pursued through automatic control of the light-oil-fired boiler and remote control of the engine from the bridge, enabling the steamship to be operated by a crew of the same size as a motor ship.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A power unit based on advanced steam technology burning fossil fuel will inevitably emit carbon dioxide, a long-lasting greenhouse gas.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] However, significant reductions of other pollutants such as CO and NOx are achievable by steam compared to other combustion technologies, since it does not involve explosive combustion, thus removing the need for add-ons (such as filters) or special preparation of fuel.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] If renewable fuel such as wood or other biofuel is used then the system could be carbon neutral.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The use of biofuel remains controversial; however, liquid biofuels are easier to manufacture for steam plant than for diesels as they do not demand the stringent fuel standards required to protect diesel injectors.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] In principle, combustion and power delivery of steam plant can be considered separate stages.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] High overall thermal efficiency may be difficult to achieve, largely due to the extra stage of generating a working fluid between combustion and power delivery attributable mainly to leakages and heat losses.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The separation of the processes allows specific problems to be addressed at each stage without revising the whole system every time.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] For instance, the boiler or steam generator can be adapted to use any heat source, whether obtained from solid, liquid or gaseous fuel, and can use waste heat.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Whatever the choice, it will have no direct effect on the design of the engine unit, as that only ever has to deal with steam.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] This project mainly includes combined electrical generation and heating systems for private homes and small villages burning wood or bamboo chips.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] This is intended to replace 2-stroke donkey engines and small diesel power plants.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Drastic reduction in noise level is one immediate benefit of a steam-powered small plant.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Ted Pritchard, of Melbourne, Australia, was intensively developing this type of unit from 2002 until his death in 2007.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The company Pritchard Power (now Uniflow Power) stated in 2010 that they continue to develop the stationary S5000, and that a prototype had been built and was being tested, and designs were being refined for market ready products.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Until 2006 a German company called *Enginion* was actively developing a *Steamcell*, a micro CHP unit about the size of a PC tower for domestic use.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] It seems that by 2008 it had merged with Berlin company AMOVIS.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Since 2012, a French company, EXOES, is selling to industrial firms a Rankine Cycle, patented, engine, which is designed to work with many fuels such as concentrated solar power, biomass, or fossil.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The system, called "SHAPE" for Sustainable Heat And Power Engine, converts the heat into electricity.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The SHAPE engine is suitable for embedded, and stationary, applications.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A SHAPE engine has been integrated into a biomass boiler, and into a Concentrated solar power system.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The company is planning to work with automobile manufactures, long-haul truck manufactures, and railway corporations.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A similar unit is marketed by Powertherm, a subsidiary of Spilling (see below).
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A company in India manufactures steam-powered generators in a range of sizes from 4 hp to 50 hp.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] They also offer a number of different mills that can be powered by their engines.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] In matter of technology, notice that the Quasiturbine is a uniflow rotary steam engine where steam intakes in hot areas, while exhausting in cold areas.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Spilling company produces a variety of small fixed stationary plant adapted to biomass combustion or power derived from waste heat or pressure recovery.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The Finnish company Steammotor Finland has developed a small rotary steam engine that runs with 800 kW steam generator.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The engines are planned to produce electricity in wood chip fired power plants.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] According to the company, the steam engine named *Quadrum* generates 27% efficiency and runs with 180 °C steam at 8 bar pressure, while a corresponding steam turbine produces just 15% efficiency, requires steam temperature of 240 °C and pressure of 40 bar.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The high efficiency comes from a patented crank mechanism, that gives a smooth, pulseless torque.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] The company believes that by further developing the construction there is potential to reach as high efficiency as 30–35%.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] During the first 1970s oil crisis, a number of investigations into steam technology were initiated by large automobile corporations although as the crisis died down, impetus was soon lost.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Australian engineer Ted Pritchard's main field of research from the late 1950s until the 1970s was the building of several efficient steam power units working on the uniflow system adapted to a small truck and two cars.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] One of the cars was achieving the lowest emissions figures of that time.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] All these engines made heavy use of flameless ceramic heat cells both for the steam generator and at strategic boost points where steam was injected into the cylinder(s).
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A design mounted on power bogies with compact water-tube boiler similar to Sentinel designs of the 1930s.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Example: Sentinel-Cammell locomotive (right).
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Both 52 8055 and the proposed 5AT are of conventional layout, with the cab at the back, while the ACE 3000 had the cab located at the front.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Other approaches are possible, especially with liquid fuel firing.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] This is a well-tried design with the potential for a large power output and would provide the driver good visibility.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Another well-tried design with large power potential.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] A future design could include shorter water tanks, and a cab at each end, to give the driver a good view in either direction.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] Another proposal for advanced steam technology is to revive the fireless locomotive, which runs on stored steam independently pre-generated.
[src:cornish-engine/advanced-steam-technology] An example is the Solar Steam Train project in Sacramento, California.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] The website has come under scrutiny from many governments starting in the late 2010s, including bans in China and Russia and in 2025 U.S.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) subpoenaed a domain registrar to identify the owner of archive.today's domain name.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] archive.today was founded in 2012 as a web archive.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] It allegedly registered its trademark in the Czech Republic in 2013.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] The site originally branded itself as archive.today, but changed the primary mirror to archive.is in May 2015.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] It began to deprecate the archive.is domain in favor of other mirrors in January 2019.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] According to the archive.today blog, the website had saved about 500 million pages by 2021, 700 terabytes in total size.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] In July 2013, archive.today began supporting the API of the Memento Project at Los Alamos National Laboratory.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] Due to budget constraints at LANL, the Memento Project was disestablished in September 2025.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] Archive.today was one of the last major active users of the Memento protocol following the project's downsizing.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] The closure of the Memento infrastructure at LANL in September 2025 came amid a broader period of increased scrutiny for the service.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] Individual profile pages on 200.zona.media link to snapshots of social media posts by relatives, obituaries in local media, and other open-source evidence used to verify each death.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] In early 2023, a team of researchers at the University of Amsterdam identified archive.today as the most-used open-access archiving service among fact-checking organisations, based on the European Digital Media Observatory's dataset on the Russo-Ukrainian war.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] On 5 August 2023, Jani Patokallio published on his blog *Gyrovague* an investigation regarding archive.today's funding sources and the founder's identity.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] On 30 October 2025, the US Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) subpoenaed archive.today's domain registrar, Tucows.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] The subpoena stated its purpose was to identify the owner(s) of the archive.today domain name, and that it was part of a criminal investigation conducted by the FBI, the nature of which was not disclosed.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] News coverage of the subpoena mentioned Patokallio's report, where Patokallio has said there were "several indications" the founder was based in Russia.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] In November 2025, the DNS provider AdGuard DNS reported that a French organization *Web Abuse Association Defense* (WAAD) had pressured it to block archive.today and its mirror domains.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] WAAD alleged that archive.today had refused to remove child sexual abuse material since 2023.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] When AdGuard contacted archive.today, the archive removed the material, stating that it had never received prior complaints about those URLs.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] AdGuard found WAAD suspicious as a recently registered association with minimal public presence, noting evidence of possible impersonation of a real French lawyer in similar WAAD complaints sent to other companies.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] AdGuard announced it would file a criminal complaint with French police.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] On 14 January 2026, it emerged that archive.today had silently modified its CAPTCHA page to send repeated requests to *Gyrovague*, thereby causing visitors to unwittingly contribute to a DDOS attack against the blog.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] The archive.today blog simultaneously posted several public criticisms of Patokallio.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] Emails released by Patokallio show archive.today requesting the temporary removal of his report and later threatening him with AI pornography.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] The community's decision was made despite concerns over maintaining content verifiability—partly undermined by the discovery of the alterations— while removing and replacing the second-largest archiving service used across the Wikimedia Foundation's projects.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] The Wikimedia Foundation had stated its readiness to take action regardless of the community verdict.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] Patokallio expressed his satisfaction with the outcome.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] This was not the first time Wikipedia had restricted links to archive.today.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] In 2013, the community blacklisted archive.is, citing concerns about botnets, linkspamming, and the opaque manner in which the site was operated.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] The decision was overturned in 2016 following a new request for comment, and archive.today was removed from the spam blacklist.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] At the time of the 2026 ban, the site was the second-largest archiving service used across all Wikimedia Foundation projects, with over 695,000 links spread across approximately 400,000 pages.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] archive.today can capture individual pages in response to explicit user requests.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] Since its beginning, it has supported crawling pages with URLs containing the now-deprecated hash-bang fragment (#!).
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] The website records only text and images, excluding XML, RTF, spreadsheet (xls or ods) and other non-static content.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] However, videos for certain sites, like Twitter, are saved.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] It keeps track of the history of snapshots saved, requesting confirmation before adding a new snapshot of an already saved page.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] Once a web page is archived, it cannot be deleted directly by any Internet user.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] Pages are captured at a browser width of 1,024 pixels.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] CSS is converted to inline CSS, removing responsive web design and selectors such as `:hover` and `:active`.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] Content generated using JavaScript during the crawling process appears in a frozen state.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] HTML class names are preserved inside the `old-class` attribute.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] When text is selected, a JavaScript applet generates a URL fragment seen in the browser's address bar that automatically highlights that portion of the text when visited again.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] Web pages can be duplicated from archive.today to web.archive.org as second-level backup, but archive.today does not save its snapshots in WARC format.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] The reverse—from web.archive.org to archive.today—is also possible, but the copy usually takes more time than a direct capture.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] While saving a page, a list of URLs for individual page elements and their content sizes, HTTP statuses and MIME types is shown.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] This list can only be viewed during the crawling process.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] Removing advertisements, popups or expanding links from archived pages is possible by asking the owner to do it on his blog.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] According to the site's FAQ, archive.today's storage layer runs on Apache Hadoop and Apache Accumulo, with all data stored on the Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS).
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] Textual content is replicated three times across servers in two data centers, both located in Europe, with at least one hosted by the French provider OVH; images are replicated twice.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] The site does not store snapshots in WARC format.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] The scraping component has used a modified version of the Chromium browser since November 2019, replacing the previous PhantomJS-based engine.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] The research toolbar enables advanced keywords operators, using `*` as the wildcard character.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] Paired quotation marks address the search to an exact sequence of keywords present in the title or in the body of the webpage, whereas the *insite* operator restricts it to a specific Internet domain.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] While saving a dynamic list, archive.today search box shows only a result that links the previous and the following section of the list (e.g.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] The other web pages saved are filtered, and sometimes may be found by one of their occurrences.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] The search feature is backed by Google CustomSearch.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] If it delivers no results, archive.today attempts to utilize Yandex Search.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] archive.today is frequently used to bypass paywalls on news websites, similarly to the defunct service 12ft.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] The practice of sharing archive.today links to circumvent paywalls has sparked legal and ethical debate in Europe.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] In the Netherlands, journalist Peter Aanzee publicly challenged a physician who shared an archive.ph link to one of his paywalled articles in *De Volkskrant*, arguing that distributing archived copies constituted copyright infringement.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] Commentators have contrasted archive.today with the Internet Archive's Wayback Machine.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] The same paywalled *Volkskrant* article shared via archive.ph was also found archived in the Wayback Machine, demonstrating that both services can be used to circumvent paywalls.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] Like the Wayback Machine, archive.today does not advertise paywall circumvention among its stated features; the ability to bypass paywalls is a byproduct of its core function of archiving web pages as they appear to visitors.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] A 2025 investigation by journalist Henk van Ess found that AI chatbots—including ChatGPT, Perplexity AI, Grok, and Claude—exploit web archives to bypass paywalls during live web searches.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] In one documented case, ChatGPT retrieved a full article from *The Economist* via archive.today and then generated a five-point economic analysis in the publication's characteristic style and terminology.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] Van Ess identified six distinct methods of paywall circumvention by AI systems, of which "archive exploitation"—finding archived copies on services such as archive.today and the Internet Archive—was the most direct.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] Unlike documented concerns about AI training unpaywalled content, this behaviour involves real-time retrieval through archived copies during individual queries, effectively extending paywall circumvention beyond human users to automated agents.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] The researchers documented that archive.is URLs were extensively shared on "fringe" communities such as 4chan's /pol/ board and the Reddit subreddit r/The_Donald, both to preserve potentially contentious content and to deny ad revenue to news outlets perceived as ideologically opposed.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] Moderation bots on r/The_Donald automatically blocked direct links to certain news sites—for example, 46% of links to the *New York Daily News* were censored—and prompted users to post archive.is URLs instead.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] The authors estimated that *The Washington Post* lost approximately US$70,000 per year in ad revenue due to the practice of sharing archived copies rather than direct links on Reddit alone.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] On Reddit, bots were responsible for posting 44% of archive.is links and 85% of Wayback Machine links across the studied subreddits, driven by moderators aiming to mitigate link rot.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] A 2023 study by researchers at the University of Amsterdam, as part of the vera.ai project, examined 1,991 fact-checking articles from the European Digital Media Observatory's "War in Ukraine" dataset.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] Of 41,758 extracted links, 6,002 were archived pages. archive.today was the most-used link archiving service, at 44.1%, ahead of the Internet Archive/Wayback Machine (29.2%) and Perma.cc (26.6%).
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] Fact-checkers primarily used these services to preserve ephemeral and platform-restricted content, such as Facebook posts that are difficult to capture due to anti-bot measures.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] In March 2019, the site was blocked for six months by several internet providers in Australia and New Zealand in the aftermath of the Christchurch mosque shootings in an attempt to limit distribution of the footage of the attack.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] According to GreatFire.org, archive.today has been blocked in mainland China since March 2016, archive.li since September 2017, archive.fo since July 2018, as well as archive.ph since December 2019.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] On 21 July 2015, the archive.today blocked access to the service from all Finnish IP addresses, stating on Twitter that they did this in order to avoid escalating a dispute they allegedly had with the Finnish government.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] Since the conflict with the Finnish blogger in early 2026, the website displays an unpassable captcha to visitors from Finland.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] In 2016, the Russian communications agency Roskomnadzor began blocking access to archive.is from Russia.
[src:cornish-engine/archive-today] On 23 March 2026, archive.today and several mirror domains were blocked by Russian authorities.
[src:cornish-engine/arthur-woolf] Woolf left Cornwall in 1785 to work for Joseph Bramah's engineering works in London.
[src:cornish-engine/arthur-woolf] He worked there and at other firms as an engineer and engine builder until 1811 experimenting with high pressure steam and a much improved boiler.
[src:cornish-engine/arthur-woolf] Michael Loam, who introduced the man engine to the UK, was trained by him.
[src:cornish-engine/arthur-woolf] When he returned to Cornwall, beam engine designs were crude, shackled by outdated Watt patents and poor engineering, struggling to compete with large water wheels, even used underground.
[src:cornish-engine/arthur-woolf] He learned from Bramah that to move forward meant adopting much improved engineering techniques, for it was Bramah who invented quality control.
[src:cornish-engine/arthur-woolf] Woolf was chief engineer to Harvey & Co of Hayle, the leading engineering and foundry works, at this time the largest in the world.
[src:cornish-engine/arthur-woolf] They eventually swallowed up the rival Copperhouse Foundry run by Sandys, Carne and Vivian.
[src:cornish-engine/arthur-woolf] For very many years they were the leading firm worldwide for drainage engines, even supplying three eight-beamed pumping engines to the Dutch government to drain the Haarlemmermeer (see Museum De Cruquius).
[src:cornish-engine/arthur-woolf] By the time Woolf retired in 1836 the Cornish engine, owing largely to his efforts, was a thing of magnificent beauty and efficiency.
[src:cornish-engine/arthur-woolf] In 1803, Woolf obtained a patent on an improved boiler for producing high pressure steam.
[src:cornish-engine/arthur-woolf] In 1804, he patented his best-known invention, a compound steam engine.
[src:cornish-engine/arthur-woolf] Woolf's engine was a parallel compound engine with two cylinders in which the steam worked in succession.
[src:cornish-engine/arthur-woolf] These were both coupled to the same end of the beam of the engine.
[src:cornish-engine/arthur-woolf] The operation of the engine can be described as being a high-pressure cylinder of Trevithick's high-pressure simple expansion engine, followed by a condensing cylinder of Watt's design.
[src:cornish-engine/arthur-woolf] Woolf had worked as an engine erector for Hornblower and was familiar with his earlier work on compound engines.
[src:cornish-engine/arthur-woolf] As a Cornishman, he was also familiar with Trevithick and his newly developed high-pressure 'puffer' engines that were then entering service.
[src:cornish-engine/arthur-woolf] He recognised that, even with the new principle of expansion, the exhaust from a Trevithick engine was still of a pressure comparable to the inlet pressure of a Watt engine.
[src:cornish-engine/arthur-woolf] From this step, it was a relatively simple matter to couple the two.
[src:cornish-engine/arthur-woolf] For most uses, the cylinders of the engine were double-acting.
[src:cornish-engine/arthur-woolf] Opposing sides of the high- and low-pressure cylinders were cross-connected to each other.
[src:cornish-engine/arthur-woolf] Where engines were used for pumping, Woolf engines were also built with paired single-acting cylinders.
[src:cornish-engine/arthur-woolf] Examples of Woolf compound rotative beam engines may be seen at Abbey Pumping Station, Blagdon Lake, Claymills Pumping Station, The Hamilton Museum of Steam & Technology, and the Western Springs Pumphouse, now part of the Museum of Transport and Technology Auckland, New Zealand.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] In most circumstances, atmospheric pressure is closely approximated by the hydrostatic pressure caused by the weight of air above the measurement point.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] As elevation increases, there is less overlying atmospheric mass, so atmospheric pressure decreases with increasing elevation.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] Because the atmosphere is thin relative to the Earth's radius – especially the dense atmospheric layer at low altitudes – the Earth's gravitational acceleration as a function of altitude can be approximated as constant and contributes little to this fall-off.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] Pressure measures force per unit area, with SI units of pascals (1 pascal = 1 newton per square meter, 1 N/m2).
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] A column of air with a cross-sectional area of 1 in2 would have a weight of about 14.7 lbf, resulting in a pressure of 14.7 lbf/in2.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] Atmospheric pressure is caused by the gravitational attraction of the planet on the atmospheric gases above the surface and is a function of the mass of the planet, the radius of the surface, and the amount and composition of the gases and their vertical distribution in the atmosphere.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] It is modified by the planetary rotation and local effects such as wind velocity, density variations due to temperature and variations in composition.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] The *mean sea-level pressure* (MSLP) is the atmospheric pressure at mean sea level.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] This is the atmospheric pressure normally given in weather reports via meteorologists on radio, television, and newspapers or on the Internet.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] The *altimeter setting* in aviation is an atmospheric pressure adjustment.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] In aviation weather reports (METAR), QNH is transmitted around the world in hectopascals or millibars (1 hectopascal = 1 millibar).
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] In the United States, Canada, and Japan altimeter setting is reported in inches of mercury (to two decimal places).
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] The United States and Canada also report *sea-level pressure* SLP, which is adjusted to sea level by a different method, in the remarks section, not in the internationally transmitted part of the code, in hectopascals or millibars.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] However, in Canada's public weather reports, sea level pressure is instead reported in kilopascals.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] In the US weather code remarks, three digits are all that are transmitted; decimal points and the one or two most significant digits are omitted: 1,013.2 hPa (14.695 psi) is transmitted as 132; 1,000 hPa (100 kPa) is transmitted as 000; 998.7 hPa is transmitted as 987; etc.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] A system transmitting the last three digits transmits the same code (800) for 1080.0 hPa as for 980.0 hPa.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] The highest *sea-level pressure* on Earth occurs in Siberia, where the Siberian High often attains a *sea-level pressure* above 1,050 hPa (15.2 psi; 31 inHg), with record highs close to 1,085 hPa (15.74 psi; 32.0 inHg).
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] The lowest measurable *sea-level pressure* is found at the centres of tropical cyclones and tornadoes, with a record low of 870 hPa (12.6 psi; 26 inHg).
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] For numerical reasons, atmospheric models such as general circulation models (GCMs) usually predict the nondimensional *logarithm of surface pressure*.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] The average value of surface pressure on Earth is 985 hPa.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] This is in contrast to mean sea-level pressure, which involves the extrapolation of pressure to sea level for locations above or below sea level.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] The average pressure at mean sea level (MSL) in the International Standard Atmosphere (ISA) is 1,013.25 hPa, or 1 atmosphere (atm), or 29.92 inches of mercury.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] Pressure (P), mass (m), and acceleration due to gravity (g) are related by P = F/A = (m*g)/A, where A is the surface area.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] Atmospheric pressure is thus proportional to the weight per unit area of the atmospheric mass above that location.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] Pressure on Earth varies with the altitude of the surface, so air pressure on mountains is usually lower than air pressure at sea level.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] Pressure varies smoothly from the Earth's surface to the top of the mesosphere.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] Although the pressure changes with the weather, NASA has averaged the conditions for all parts of the earth year-round.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] As altitude increases, atmospheric pressure decreases.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] One can calculate the atmospheric pressure at a given altitude.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] Temperature and humidity also affect the atmospheric pressure.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] Pressure is proportional to temperature and inversely related to humidity, and both of these are necessary to compute an accurate figure.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] The graph on the rightabove was developed for a temperature of 15 °C and a relative humidity of 0%.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] At low altitudes above sea level, the pressure decreases by about 1.2 kPa (12 hPa) for every 100 meters.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] Atmospheric pressure varies widely on Earth, and differences in pressure are important in studying weather and climate.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] Some variations in pressure are very regular.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] One important source of variation is atmospheric tides.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] Atmospheric tides are strongest in tropical zones, with an amplitude of a few hectopascals, and almost zero in polar areas.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] Tropical tidal variations in pressure consist principally of two superimposed harmonics – a circadian (24 h) cycle and a semi-circadian (12 h) cycle.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] The highest adjusted-to-sea level barometric pressure ever recorded on Earth above 750 meters was 1,084.8 hPa (32.03 inHg; 1.0706 atm), measured in Tosontsengel, Mongolia on 19 December 2001.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] The highest adjusted-to-sea level barometric pressure ever recorded below 750 meters was at Agata, in Evenk Autonomous Okrug, Russia (66°53' N, 93°28' E, elevation: 261 m, 856 ft), on 31 December 1968 of 1,083.8 hPa (32.005 inHg).
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] The Dead Sea, the lowest sea surface on Earth, at 430 metres (1,410 ft) below sea level, has a correspondingly high typical atmospheric pressure of 1,065 hPa.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] A below-sea-level surface pressure record of 1,081.8 hPa (31.95 inHg; 1.0677 atm) was set on 21 February 1961.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] The lowest non-tornadic atmospheric pressure ever measured was 870 hPa (26 inHg; 0.86 atm), set on 12 October 1979, during Typhoon Tip in the western Pacific Ocean.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] The measurement was based on an instrumental observation made from a reconnaissance aircraft.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] One atmosphere (101.325 kPa or 14.7 psi) is also the pressure caused by the weight of a column of freshwater of approximately 10.3 m (33.8 ft).
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] Thus, a diver 10.3 m under water experiences a pressure of about 2 atmospheres (1 atm of air plus 1 atm of water).
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] Conversely, 10.3 m is the maximum height to which water can be raised using suction under standard atmospheric conditions.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] Low pressures, such as natural gas lines, are sometimes specified in inches of water, typically written as *w.c.* (water column) gauge or *w.g.* (inches water) gauge.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] A typical gas-using residential appliance in the US is rated for a maximum of 1⁄2 psi (3.4 kPa; 34 mbar), which is approximately 14 w.g.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] Similar metric units with a wide variety of names and notation based on millimeters, centimeters or meters are now less commonly used.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] Pure water boils at 100 °C (212 °F) at Earth's standard atmospheric pressure.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] The boiling point is the temperature at which the vapour pressure is equal to the atmospheric pressure around the liquid.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] Because of this, the boiling point of liquids is lower at lower pressure and higher at higher pressure.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] Cooking at high elevations, therefore, requires adjustments to recipes or pressure cooking.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] A rough approximation of elevation can be obtained by measuring the temperature at which water boils; in the mid-19th century, this method was used by explorers.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] Conversely, if one wishes to evaporate a liquid at a lower temperature, for example in distillation, the atmospheric pressure may be lowered by using a vacuum pump, as in a rotary evaporator.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] An important application of the knowledge that atmospheric pressure varies directly with altitude was in determining the height of hills and mountains, thanks to reliable pressure measurement devices.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] In 1774, Nevil Maskelyne was confirming Newton's theory of gravitation at and on Schiehallion mountain in Scotland, and he needed to measure elevations on the mountain's sides accurately.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] This event is known as the Schiehallion experiment.
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] William Roy, using barometric pressure, was able to confirm Maskelyne's height determinations; the agreement was within one meter (3.28 feet).
[src:cornish-engine/atmospheric-pressure] This method became and continues to be useful for survey work and map making.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A **high pressure watertube boiler** (also spelled *water-tube* and *water tube*) is a type of boiler in which water circulates in tubes heated externally by fire.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Fuel is burned inside the furnace, creating hot gas which boils water in the steam-generating tubes.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In smaller boilers, additional generating tubes are separate in the furnace, while larger utility boilers rely on the water-filled tubes that make up the walls of the furnace to generate steam.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The heated water/steam mixture then rises into the steam drum.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Here, saturated steam is drawn off the top of the drum.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In some services, the steam passes through tubes in the hot gas path (a superheater) to become superheated.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Superheated steam is a dry gas and therefore is typically used to drive turbines, since water droplets can severely damage turbine blades.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Saturated water at the bottom of the steam drum returns to the lower drum via large-bore 'downcomer tubes', where it pre-heats the feedwater supply.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] (In large utility boilers, the feedwater is supplied to the steam drum and the downcomers supply water to the bottom of the waterwalls).
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] To increase economy of the boiler, exhaust gases are also used to pre-heat combustion air blown into the burners, and to warm the feedwater supply in an economizer.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Such watertube boilers in thermal power stations are also called *steam generating units*.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The older fire-tube boiler design, in which the water surrounds the heat source and gases from combustion pass through tubes within the water space, is typically a much weaker structure and is rarely used for pressures above 2.4 MPa (350 psi).
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A significant advantage of the watertube boiler is that there is less chance of a catastrophic failure: there is not a large volume of water in the boiler nor are there large mechanical elements subject to failure.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A water-tube boiler was patented by Blakey of England in 1766 and was made by Dallery of France in 1780.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] "The ability of watertube boilers to be designed without the use of excessively large and thick-walled pressure vessels makes these boilers particularly attractive in applications that require dry, high-pressure, high-energy steam, including steam turbine power generation".
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Besides, they are frequently employed in power generation plants where large quantities of steam (ranging up to 500 kg/s) having high pressures i.e. approximately 16 megapascals (160 bar) and high temperatures reaching up to 550 °C are generally required.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] For example, the Ivanpah solar-power station uses two Rentech Type-D watertube boilers for plant warmup, and when operating as a fossil-fueled power station.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Modern boilers for power generation are almost entirely water-tube designs, owing to their ability to operate at higher pressures.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Where process steam is required for heating or as a chemical component, then there is still a small niche for fire-tube boilers.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] One notable exception is in typical nuclear-power stations (Pressurized Water Reactors), where the steam generators are generally configured similar to firetube boiler designs.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In these applications the hot gas path through the "Firetubes" actually carries the very hot/high pressure primary coolant from the reactor, and steam is generated on the external surface of the tubes.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Their ability to work at higher pressures has led to marine boilers being almost entirely watertube.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This change began around 1900, and traced the adoption of turbines for propulsion rather than reciprocating (i.e. piston) engines – although watertube boilers were also used with reciprocating engines, and firetube boilers were also used in many marine turbine applications.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] There has been no significant adoption of water-tube boilers for railway locomotives.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A handful of experimental designs were produced, but none of them were successful or led to their widespread use.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Most water-tube railway locomotives, especially in Europe, used the Schmidt system.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Most were compounds, and a few uniflows.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The Norfolk and Western Railway's *Jawn Henry* was an exception, because it used a steam turbine combined with an electric transmission.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Not successful and re-boilered with a conventional boiler.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A slightly more successful adoption was the use of hybrid water-tube/fire-tube systems.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] As the hottest part of a locomotive boiler is the firebox, it was an effective design to use water-tubes here and a conventional fire-tube boiler as an economiser (i.e. pre-heater) in the usual position.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] One famous example of this was the USA Baldwin 4-10-2 No.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Built as a compound with a boiler pressure of 2,400 kilopascals (350 psi) it successfully covered over 160,000 kilometres (100,000 mi) in service.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] After a year however, it became clear that any improvements were overwhelmed by the extra costs, and it was retired as a museum display at the Franklin Institute in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A series of twelve experimental locomotives were constructed at the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad's Mt.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Clare shops under the supervision of George H.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Emerson, but none of them were replicated in any numbers.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The only water-tube locomotive boiler used in any large numbers was the Brotan boiler, invented by Johann Brotan in Austria in 1902 and found sparsely throughout Europe, although Hungary had around 1,000 in service.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Like the Baldwin 60000, it combined a water-tube firebox with a fire-tube barrel.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The Brotan's original characteristic was a long steam drum running *above* the main barrel, resembling a Flaman boiler in appearance.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] While traction engines were usually built with locomotive boiler as its frame, other types of steam road vehicles such as lorries and cars used a wide range of different boiler types.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Road transport pioneers Goldsworthy Gurney and Walter Hancock both used water-tube boilers in their steam carriages around 1830.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Most undertype wagons used water-tube boilers.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Many manufacturers used variants of the vertical cross-tube boiler, including Atkinson, Clayton, Garrett and Sentinel.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Other types include the Clarkson 'thimble tube' and the Foden O-type wagon's pistol-shaped boiler.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Steam fire-engine makers such as Merryweather usually used water-tube boilers for their rapid steam-raising capacity.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Many steam cars used water-tube boilers, and the Bolsover Express company even made a water-tube replacement for the Stanley Steamer fire-tube boiler.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The 'D-type' is the most common type of small- to medium-sized boilers, similar to the one shown in the schematic diagram.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] It is used in both stationary and marine applications.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] It consists of a large steam drum vertically connected to a smaller water drum (a.k.a.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] "mud drum") via multiple steam-generating tubes.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] These drums and tubes as well as the oil-fired burner are enclosed by water-walls - additional water-filled tubes spaced close together so as to prevent gas flow between them.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] These water wall tubes are connected to both the steam and water drums, so that they act as a combination of preheaters and downcomers as well as decreasing heat loss to the boiler shell.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The M-type boilers were used in many US World War II warships including hundreds of *Fletcher*-class destroyers.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Three sets of tubes form the shape of an M, and create a separately fired superheater that allows better superheat temperature control.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In addition to the mud drum shown on a D-type boiler, an M-type has a water-screen header and a waterwall header at the bottom of the two additional rows of vertical tubes and downcomers.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The *low water content* boiler has a lower and upper header connected by watertubes that are directly impinged upon from the burner.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This is a "furnace-less" boiler that can generate steam and react quickly to changes in load.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Designed by the American firm of Babcock & Wilcox, this type has a single drum, with feedwater drawn from the bottom of the drum into a header that supplies inclined water-tubes.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The watertubes supply steam back into the top of the drum.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Furnaces are located below the tubes and drum.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This type of boiler was used by the Royal Navy's *Leander*-class frigates and in United States Navy New Orleans-class cruisers.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The Stirling boiler has near-vertical, almost-straight watertubes that zig-zag between a number of steam and water drums.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Usually there are three banks of tubes in a "four drum" layout, but certain applications use variations designed with a different number of drums and banks.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] They are mainly used as stationary boilers, owing to their large size, although the large grate area does also encourage their ability to burn a wide range of fuels.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Originally coal-fired in power stations, they also became widespread in industries that produced combustible waste and required process steam.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Paper pulp mills could burn waste bark, sugar refineries their bagasse waste.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Named after its designers, the then Poplar-based Yarrow Shipbuilders, this type of three-drum boiler has three drums in a delta formation connected by watertubes.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The drums are linked by straight watertubes, allowing easy tube-cleaning.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This does, however, mean that the tubes enter the drums at varying angles, a more difficult joint to caulk.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Outside the firebox, a pair of cold-leg pipes between each drum act as downcomers.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Due to its three drums, the Yarrow boiler has a greater water capacity.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Hence, this type is usually used in older marine boiler applications.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Its compact size made it attractive for use in transportable power generation units during World War II.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In order to make it transportable, the boiler and its auxiliary equipment (fuel oil heating, pumping units, fans etc.), turbines, and condensers were mounted on wagons to be transported by rail.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The White-Forster type is similar to the Yarrow, but with tubes that are gradually curved.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This makes their entry into the drums perpendicular, thus simpler to make a reliable seal.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Thornycroft & Company, the Thornycroft type features a single steam drum with two sets of watertubes either side of the furnace.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] These tubes, especially the central set, have sharp curves.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Apart from obvious difficulties in cleaning them, this may also give rise to bending forces as the tubes warm up, tending to pull them loose from the tubeplate and creating a leak.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] There are two furnaces, venting into a common exhaust, giving the boiler a wide base tapering profile.
[src:cornish-engine/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In a forced circulation boiler, a pump is added to speed up the flow of water through the tubes.
[src:cornish-engine/baker-valve-gear] After about 1910, the **Baker valve gear** was the main competitor to Walschaerts valve gear for steam locomotives in the United States.
[src:cornish-engine/baker-valve-gear] Strictly speaking it was not a valve gear but a variable expansion mechanism adapted to the Walschaerts layout replacing the expansion link and sliding die block.
[src:cornish-engine/baker-valve-gear] The Baker arrangement used more pivot bearings or *pin joints*, but avoided the die slip inherent to the expansion link, with the aim of lessening wear and the need for service; it could also facilitate longer valve travel.
[src:cornish-engine/baker-valve-gear] In the early 1900s there were many efforts to create a new valve gear to replace the by-then-standard Walschaerts valve gear.
[src:cornish-engine/baker-valve-gear] In the United States the Young, Southern, Caprotti and Franklin patterns were used on a few classes, but only the Baker pattern won more than limited acceptance.
[src:cornish-engine/baker-valve-gear] Baker Company, of Swanton, Ohio; a builder of steam traction engines.
[src:cornish-engine/baker-valve-gear] The idea came from an employee called Gifford but was developed by the Baker company with the first patents being issued in 1903 and with patents issued through at least November, 1912.
[src:cornish-engine/baker-valve-gear] The Baker Locomotive Valve Gear was produced by the Pilliod Co. of Swanton, Ohio.
[src:cornish-engine/baker-valve-gear] Subsequent versions were produced up to the end of steam service.
[src:cornish-engine/baker-valve-gear] It was particularly popular on the Norfolk and Western Railway, and almost all later N&W engines used it.
[src:cornish-engine/baker-valve-gear] Other extensive users included the Chesapeake and Ohio Railway, the Nickel Plate Road, the New York Central Railroad and the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad.
[src:cornish-engine/baker-valve-gear] There was always debate about the advantages of Baker gear, the main criticism being the number of pin joints and possible lost motion.
[src:cornish-engine/baker-valve-gear] While popular with railroads on the east, western states tended to continue with the Walschaerts pattern.
[src:cornish-engine/baker-valve-gear] In Britain, Baker gear was popular amongst model engineers but in full-size practice the length of the yoke and the width of the assembly may have been difficult to accommodate within the restricted loading gauge.
[src:cornish-engine/baker-valve-gear] Other locomotives to use Baker valve gear were the New Zealand Railways J class, Ja class, Jb class, some Ka class, and the South Australian Railways 620 class.
[src:cornish-engine/baker-valve-gear] The Baker valve gear replaces the expansion link of the Walschaerts gear with an assembly of levers and links which produces the same effect of allowing continuous variation valve travel.
[src:cornish-engine/baker-valve-gear] The remainder of the gear is the same, so that the return crank and combination lever take the same form, although the proportions are usually modified.
[src:cornish-engine/baker-valve-gear] The Pilliod Co. sold the gear as a single assembly which was mounted on the frame in the location ordinarily occupied by the Walschaerts expansion link.
[src:cornish-engine/baker-valve-gear] The parts were arranged so that when the yoke was centered, the connection of the main link to the bellcrank was in a line with the two pivots on the yoke.
[src:cornish-engine/baker-valve-gear] At this point, the back and forth motion of the lower end of the main link left the top relatively motionless as main link swung back and forth on the swing links.
[src:cornish-engine/baker-valve-gear] In forward motion, the yoke was pushed forward, so that its upper pivot was in front of the bell crank-main link connection.
[src:cornish-engine/baker-valve-gear] Moving the eccentric arm back and forth lowered and raised the top of the main link.
[src:cornish-engine/baker-valve-gear] This motion was translated by the bellcrank into back and forth motion of the radius rod.
[src:cornish-engine/baker-valve-gear] The angle of the yoke controlled the relative motion, and therefore the cutoff; tilting the yoke backwards reversed the motion of the radius rod.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] A **bash valve** is a valve within a piston engine, used to control the admission of the working fluid.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] They are directly actuated valves, operated by contact between the piston and the valve tip.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] Bash valves have the advantage of great simplicity, for manufacture and operation.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] Their disadvantages are that their opening and closing times are relatively crudely controlled, compared to other types of valve gear.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] The valve is usually constructed as a circular poppet valve with a conical seat, inserted into the cylinder from the outside.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] A protrusion on the inside is hit by the piston as it approaches top dead centre, forcing the valve open.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] Bash valves are usually held closed by the pressure of fluid in the reservoir behind them.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] There may be a light spring to assist closing when the reservoir is empty.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] For this reason they are used as inlet valves, not exhaust.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] An exhaust bash valve would have the cylinder pressure and the piston actuation both acting to open it, with nothing to close it.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] Bash valves are not widely used in steam engines, although they are known.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] Most examples were applied to some form of uniflow steam engine; unlike the more common slide and piston-valved engines with their bidirectional-flow ports, uniflow engines use inlet ports at the cylinder ends and an exhaust near the centre.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] Although the opening time of a bash valve is fixed, imprecisely controlled and always occurs near top dead centre, this is not a major drawback for a steam engine.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] A more important requirement is the ability to accurately control the closing time of the valve, and for its duration to be adjustable in order to 'drive' the engine, according to varying load.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] Some designs of uniflow engine have used a combined mechanical and electromagnetic valve to do this.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] The valve is opened mechanically, then held by an electromagnet.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] This requires less electrical power to merely hold the valve than to open it.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] A patent for such an engine was granted to Sturtevant in 1968.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] The same idea has recently been revived as the main feature of an Advanced Uniflow Steam Engine.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] In this engine, a second valve is used for exhaust purposes in the later part of the cycle too, although this one is bashed shut, rather than opened.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] Bash valves have also been used for the *ad hoc* conversion of commonplace petrol small engines, such as lawnmowers, into hobbyist steam engines.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] The original petrol engine sparkplug mounting hole is used as the location for a new piston-actuated bash valve, together with the original exhaust valve.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] Performance and efficiency are not a need of such projects.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] One successful application for bash valves has been to pneumatic motors.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] Owing to the characteristics of compressed air pneumatic power, their simplicity is valuable and their inefficiencies with other fluids are less important.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] Compressed air is supplied cold to the motor.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] Energy is represented solely by the pressure of the air not, unlike steam, by the combination of pressure and temperature.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] Efficient operation of a steam engine relies upon expansion of the steam during the piston stroke, which relies upon accurate valve timing and an early closure of the valve.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] During the expansion phase of the steam it does not expand in a simple isothermal fashion, but does so adiabatically, much of the energy having been supplied as heat rather than pressure.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] The compressed air motor is thermodynamically simpler.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] This means that expansion is less important, valve timings are thus longer and less crucial and so a simple valve may be adequate.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] To provide long opening times, the bash valve normally incorporates some form of tappet mechanism.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] Rather than a valve that is held open by the piston directly, the valve becomes double-acting and is opened by the piston's impact at one end of the stroke and closed by a further impact at the other end of the stroke.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] The tappet and valve are commonly separate, allowing the valve to remain in a well-defined fully open position throughout the stroke, however the tappet is bounced around by the piston.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] Where a reciprocating action is produced, such as for a rock drill, the valve may be actuated either by inertia of the frame or by the movement of the working piston.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] As the piston hammers back and forth, it impacts a small tappet, which in turn moves the air valve and so reverses the flow of air to the piston.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] One form of this, the arc tappet valve, was an important feature of the Ingersoll rock drill, the first successful compressed air rock drill for use in mining and tunneling.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] This used a valve that rotated in a slight arc, rather than sliding.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] The valve was double-acting, controlling the air supply for both the power and the return stroke.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] The innovation that made this valve so reliable, thus successful, was a separate tappet that was actuated by the piston in passing at the middle of the stroke, rather than being hammered by a jarring direct impact of the piston.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] The mid-stroke actuation also opened the valve passageways earlier, before top dead centre, allowing in air that provided a cushioning effect.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] This further improved the action of the drill, giving a powerful stroke on the working piston and drill rod, but with less damaging hammering to the frame of the drill.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] Bash valves are not used in such engines.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] The cylinder peak pressures of an Otto cycle engine are too high for such a valve to remain on its seat.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] Bash valves are also used in a 'single-shot' situation, where a valve is opened once and then remains open until the contents of a pressure vessel are released.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] Such valves are used in some fire extinguishers and pre-charged air rifles.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] These valves are arranged so that once lifted off their seat, pressure underneath the valve becomes sufficient to keep the valve raised and so it remains open until the pressure reservoir is empty.
[src:cornish-engine/bash-valve] The valve is then closed by a light spring.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] A **Cornish engine** is a type of steam engine developed in Cornwall, England, mainly for pumping water from a mine.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] It is a form of beam engine that uses steam at a higher pressure than the earlier engines designed by James Watt.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] The engines were also used for powering man engines to assist the underground miners' journeys to and from their working levels, for winching materials into and out of the mine, and for powering on-site ore stamping machinery.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] Cornwall long had tin, copper and other metal ore mines, but if mining were to take place at greater depths, a means to dewater the mine would be needed.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] Lifting the weight of water up from the depths requires great amounts of work input.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] This energy may be weakly supplied by horse power or a waterwheel to operate pumps, but horses have limited power and waterwheels need a suitable stream of water.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] Accordingly, the innovation of coal-fired steam power to work pumps was more versatile and effective to the mining industry than primitive means.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] The mine *Wheal Vor* had one of the earliest Newcomen engines (in-cylinder condensing engines, utilising sub-atmospheric pressure) before 1714, but Cornwall has no coalfield and coal imported from south Wales was expensive.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] The cost of fuel for pumping was thus a significant part of mining costs.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] Later, many of the more efficient early Watt engines (using an external condenser) were erected by Boulton and Watt in Cornwall.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] They charged the mine owners a royalty based on a share of the fuel saving.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] The fuel efficiency of an engine was measured by its "duty", expressed in the work (in foot-pounds) generated by a bushel (94 pounds (43 kg)) of coal.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] Early Watt engines had a duty of 20 million, and later ones over 30 million.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] The principal advantage of the Cornish engine was its increased efficiency, accomplished by making more economical use of higher-pressure steam.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] At the time, improvements in efficiency were important in Cornwall because of the high cost of coal; there are no coal fields in Cornwall and all the coal used had to be brought in from outside the county, typically from Wales.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] Increasing the boiler pressure above the virtually atmospheric pressure steam used by James Watt was an essential element of the improvement in efficiency of the Cornish engine.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] Simply increasing the boiler pressure would have made an engine more powerful without increasing its efficiency.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] The key advance was allowing the steam to expand in the cylinder.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] While James Watt had conceived of the idea of allowing expansive working of steam—and included it in his 1782 patent, he realized that the low steam pressure of his application made the improvement in efficiency negligible, and so did not pursue it.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] In a Watt engine, steam is admitted throughout the piston's power stroke.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] At the end of the stroke, the steam is exhausted, and any remaining energy is wasted in the condenser, where the steam is cooled back to water.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] In a Cornish engine, by contrast, the intake valve is shut off midway through the power stroke, allowing the steam in the cylinder to expand through the rest of the stroke to a lower pressure.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] This results in the capture of a greater proportion of its energy, and less heat being lost to the condenser, than in a Watt engine.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] Other characteristics include insulation of steam lines and the cylinder, and steam jacketing the cylinder, both of which had previously been used by Watt.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] Few Cornish engines remain in their original locations, the majority having been scrapped when their related industrial firm closed.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] The Cornish engine developed irregular power throughout the cycle, completely pausing at one point while having rapid motion on the down stroke, making it unsuitable for rotary motion and most industrial applications.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] This also requires some unusual valve gear, see Cornish engine valve gear.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] Part way down the stroke, the pressurized steam inlet valve is closed.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] The steam above the piston then expands through the rest of the stroke, while the low-pressure steam on the other side (bottom) of the piston continues to be drawn into the condenser, thereby maintaining the partial vacuum in that part of the cylinder.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] At the bottom of the stroke, the exhaust valve to the condenser is closed and the equilibrium valve is opened.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] The weight of the pump equipment down in the mine, transferred by the walking beam, draws the piston up, and as the piston comes up, steam is transferred through the equilibrium pipe from above the piston to the bottom of the cylinder below the piston.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] When the piston reaches the top of the cylinder, the cycle is ready to repeat.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] The next stroke may occur immediately, or it may be delayed by a timing device such as a cataract, if it was not necessary for the engine to work at its maximum rate, reducing the rate of operation saved fuel.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] The engine is single-acting, and the steam piston is pulled up by the weight of the pump piston and rodding.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] Steam may be supplied at a pressure of up to 50 pounds per square inch (340 kPa).
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] The Cornish engine depended on the use of steam pressure above atmospheric pressure, as devised by Richard Trevithick in the 19th century.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] His early puffer engines discharged steam into the atmosphere.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] This differed from the Watt steam engine, which moved the condensing steam from the cylinder to a condenser separate from the cylinder; hence Watt's engine depended on the creation of a vacuum when the steam was condensed.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] Trevithick's later engines (in the 1810s) combined the two principles, starting with high-pressure steam which was then passed to the other side of the piston, where it condensed and there it acted as a sub-atmospheric pressure engine.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] In a parallel development Arthur Woolf developed the compound steam engine, in which the steam expanded in two cylinders successively, each of which were at pressures above atmospheric.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] A test was carried out between a Trevithick type single-cylinder engine and a Woolf compound engine at Wheal Alfred in 1825, when both achieved a duty of slightly more than 40 million.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] The next improvement was achieved in the late 1820s by Samuel Grose, who decreased the heat loss by insulating the pipes, cylinders, and boilers of the engines, improving the duty to more than 60 million at Wheal Hope and later to almost 80 million at Wheal Towan.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] Nevertheless, the best duty was usually a short-lived achievement due to general deterioration of machinery, leaks from boilers, and the deterioration of boiler plates (meaning that pressure had to be reduced).
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] Minor improvements increased the duty somewhat, but the engine seems to have reached its practical limits by the mid-1840s.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] With pressures of up to 50 pounds per square inch (340 kPa), the forces are likely to have caused machinery breakages.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] The same improvements in duty occurred in engines operating Cornish stamps and whims, but generally came slightly later.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] In both cases the best duty was lower than for pumping engines, particularly so for whim engines, whose work was discontinuous.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] The impetus for the improvement of the steam engine came from Cornwall due to the high price of coal there, but both capital and maintenance costs were higher than a Watt steam engine.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] This long delayed the installation of Cornish engines outside Cornwall.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] A secondhand Cornish engine was installed by Thomas Wicksteed at the Old Ford waterworks of the East London Waterworks company in 1838, and compared to a Watt engine with favourable results, because the price of coal in London was even higher than in Cornwall.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] Cornish engines became widely used for water supply around the world.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] In the main textile manufacturing areas, such as Manchester and Leeds, the coal price was too low to make replacement economic.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] Only in the late 1830s did textile manufacturers begin moving to high-pressure engines, usually by adding a high-pressure cylinder, forming a compound engine, rather than following the usual Cornish practice.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] Several Cornish engines are preserved in England.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] The London Museum of Water & Steam has the largest collection of Cornish engines in the world.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] Two examples also survive at the Cornish Mines and Engines museum on the site of East Pool mine near the town of Pool, Cornwall.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] Another example is at Poldark Mine at Trenear, Cornwall – a Harvey of Hayle Cornish Beam Engine from about 1840–1850, originally employed at Bunny Tin Mine and later at Greensplat China Clay Pit, both near St Austell.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] It no longer works as a steam engine but is instead moved by a hydraulic mechanism.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] In use at Greensplat until 1959, it is the last Cornish engine to have worked commercially in Cornwall.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] The Cruquius pumping station in the Netherlands contains a Cornish engine with the largest diameter cylinder ever built for a Cornish engine, at 3.5 metres (140 inches) diameter.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] The engine, which was built by Harvey & Co in Hayle, Cornwall, has eight beams connected to the one cylinder, each beam driving a single pump.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] The engine was restored to working order between 1985 and 2000, although it is now operated by an oil-filled hydraulic system, since restoration to steam operation was not viable.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] The 1879 pair of engines preserved at Dalton Pumping Station in County Durham were the only Cornish Engines designed to run on superheated steam.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] One of the last Cornish engines to be built was installed at the Dorothea Slate Quarry in 1904, where it remains within its engine house.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] The Cornish Engines Preservation Committee, an early industrial archaeology organisation, was formed in 1935 to preserve the Levant winding engine.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] The committee was later renamed for Richard Trevithick.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] They acquired another winding engine and two pumping engines.
[src:cornish-engine/cornish-engine] They publish a newsletter, a journal and many books on Cornish engines, the mining industry, engineers, and other industrial archaeological topics.
